  "prompt": "How do I get a copyright to a video that I uploaded on YouTube?",
  "response": "When you upload a video to YouTube, you automatically have the copyright to your original content. Here are some steps to protect your copyright:\n\n1. Understand automatic copyright:\n- Original content you create is automatically copyrighted\n- No formal registration is required\n\n2. Add a copyright notice to your video:\n- Include a watermark or text with your copyright information\n- Example: \"\u00a9 [Your Name] [Year]\"\n\n3. Use YouTube's Content ID:\n- Helps track and protect your original content\n- Prevents unauthorized use of your video\n\n4. Consider formal copyright registration:\n- Optional, but provides additional legal protection\n- Register with the U.S. Copyright Office\n- Can be done online at copyright.gov\n- Costs around $45-$65 per registration\n\n5. Enable YouTube copyright settings:\n- Go to YouTube Studio\n- Select \"Monetization\" settings\n- Choose copyright protection options\n\n6. Use YouTube's copyright tools:\n- File a copyright takedown notice if someone uses your content without permission\n- Use the Copyright Match Tool to find potential unauthorized uses\n\nRemember, uploading to YouTube doesn't automatically prevent others from using your content, so stay vigilant and proactive in protecting your work.",
